#compdef rustormy
# =============================================================================
# rustormy — Tairesh's "Minimal neofetch-like weather CLI" — a
#            Rust CLI fetching weather data from multiple cloud
#            APIs (Open-Meteo, OpenWeatherMap, WorldWeatherOnline,
#            WeatherAPI, WeatherBit, Tomorrow.io, Yr.no) and
#            displaying it as neofetch-style ASCII art with
#            temperature + wind + humidity panels.
#            Distinguishing from wttr.in, weather-cli, openweather-
#            cli, and other weather CLIs by:
#              - SEVEN BACKEND PROVIDERS with automatic FALLBACK
#                chain — primary provider fails → tries next:
#                  * Open-Meteo (default, free, no API key)
#                  * OpenWeatherMap (free tier with API key)
#                  * WorldWeatherOnline (paid)
#                  * WeatherAPI (free tier with API key)
#                  * WeatherBit (paid)
#                  * Tomorrow.io (paid)
#                  * Yr.no / MET Norway (free, no API key)
#              - NEOFETCH-STYLE ASCII ART — weather conditions
#                rendered as ASCII art icons (clear / partly-
#                cloudy / cloudy / light-showers / heavy-showers
#                / light-snow / heavy-snow / thunderstorm / fog /
#                unknown) side-by-side with text data
#              - LIVE MODE via -l/--live — continuously refresh
#                every 5 minutes (or specified --interval)
#                rendering live with crossterm for full-screen
#                ANSI output
#              - GEOCODING + CACHING — city name lookup uses
#                geocoding API (Open-Meteo geocoding), with
#                results cached in directories-resolved cache
#                directory (~/.cache/rustormy on Linux); --no-
#                cache disables; --clear-cache clears
#              - 4 LANGUAGES — en / ru / es / ko translations for
#                weather descriptions
#              - 3 OUTPUT FORMATS — text (default, ASCII art),
#                json (structured), with text-mode subvariants
#                (full / compact / one-line)
#              - TIMEOUT + USER-AGENT — reqwest blocking client
#                built with custom timeout + User-Agent header
#                identifying as "rustormy/<version>"
#              - PROVIDER ENUM via clap ValueEnum — provider
#                names are snake_case CLI args (open_meteo /
#                open_weather_map / etc.)
#              - LAT/LON OR CITY — either coordinates (-y/--lat
#                + -x/--lon, allow_negative_numbers = true) or
#                city name (-c/--city); city is geocoded to
#                coordinates first
#            Used by: terminal-aesthetic users wanting weather
#            in their tmux status / dashboard, multi-provider
#            weather data validation, and as a reference
#            implementation of reqwest blocking + clap derive +
#            crossterm + directories + multi-API-fallback
#            composition in Rust.
#
# Author:  Tairesh (tairesh@protonmail.com on GitHub) — Rust
#          developer, also maintains other neofetch-aesthetic
#          CLI utilities.  rustormy released ~2024; active
#          development through 2026.  License: MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/Tairesh/rustormy
#          https://github.com/Tairesh/rustormy/blob/main/src/config/cli.rs
#          https://github.com/Tairesh/rustormy/blob/main/src/app.rs
#          https://github.com/Tairesh/rustormy/blob/main/src/models.rs
#          https://github.com/Tairesh/rustormy/blob/main/Cargo.toml
# CLI:     src/config/cli.rs — uses clap v4 derive (#[derive(Parser)],
#          ArgAction::SetTrue, ArgAction::Count, value_enum,
#          alias = "...").  Headline library: **reqwest**
#          (clap is documented extensively in other Rust
#          completions; reqwest is the new variant being
#          documented here, opening Axis 16 — HTTP Clients).
# Library: reqwest (https://github.com/seanmonstar/reqwest —
#          "An easy and powerful Rust HTTP Client" — Sean
#          McArthur (seanmonstar on GitHub), Hyperium project).
#          Distinct from all previously-documented Rust
#          libraries by being:
#             1. ASYNC + BLOCKING DUAL API — reqwest offers
#                BOTH an async API (reqwest::Client) using
#                tokio, AND a blocking API (reqwest::blocking::
#                Client) for synchronous code; users opt into
#                blocking via Cargo feature "blocking":
#                  use reqwest::blocking::Client;
#                  let client = Client::builder()
#                      .timeout(Duration::from_secs(30))
#                      .user_agent("rustormy/1.0")
#                      .build()?;
#                  let body = client.get("https://api.example.com")
#                      .send()?.text()?;
#             2. BUILDER PATTERN — ClientBuilder + RequestBuilder
#                provide fluent configuration:
#                  client.get(url)
#                      .query(&[("city", city)])
#                      .header("Authorization", token)
#                      .timeout(Duration::from_secs(10))
#                      .send()
#             3. SERDE INTEGRATION via "json" feature — direct
#                deserialization from response body:
#                  let weather: Weather = response.json()?;
#                  // Calls serde_json::from_reader internally
#             4. TLS BACKENDS — default rustls (pure Rust) but
#                opt-in native-tls (OpenSSL/SChannel/Secure
#                Transport) via Cargo feature; default-features
#                = false + features = ["rustls-tls"] for
#                rustls-only builds with NO C dependencies
#             5. HTTP/2 + HTTP/3 SUPPORT — multiplexed HTTP/2
#                via hyper; experimental HTTP/3 via quinn (h3
#                crate)
#             6. COOKIE STORE — opt-in cookie-store via "cookies"
#                feature for session-based APIs
#             7. PROXY SUPPORT — HTTP / HTTPS / SOCKS5 proxy
#                support; honor HTTP_PROXY / HTTPS_PROXY env
#                vars
#             8. MULTIPART + FORM ENCODING — first-class
#                multipart/form-data and application/x-www-form-
#                urlencoded body encoding
#             9. BUILT ON HYPER — reqwest is high-level wrapper
#                over hyper (lower-level HTTP library by same
#                author Sean McArthur).  hyper used as primary
#                HTTP machinery, reqwest provides the friendly
#                high-level API
#            10. SEAN MCARTHUR / HYPERIUM ECOSYSTEM — Sean also
#                maintains: hyper (HTTP/1.1 + HTTP/2 backbone),
#                tower (middleware), tonic (gRPC), warp (web
#                framework).  Hyperium = the Rust HTTP
#                infrastructure foundation used by 80% of Rust
#                HTTP code
# License: MIT OR Apache-2.0 (reqwest); MIT (rustormy)
# Status:  reqwest — 10,500+ stars on seanmonstar/reqwest,
#          ~180M crates.io downloads (TOP-50 Rust crate by
#          download count); foundational HTTP client used by:
#            * cargo (Rust package manager)
#            * gix / gitoxide (Git in Rust)
#            * starship (cross-shell prompt)
#            * spotify-tui
#            * lsd (ls deluxe)
#            * onefetch
#            * gitui
#            * navi (interactive cheatsheets)
#            * mdbook (Rust book builder)
#            * cargo-watch
#            * cargo-deny
#            * cargo-audit
#            * cargo-edit
#            * miri compiler
#            * 100,000+ Rust applications
#          rustormy — 85+ stars on Tairesh/rustormy, used by
#          terminal-aesthetic communities for tmux/dashboard
#          weather widgets.
#
